s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3513:\"<p>One of the big changes in Autoptimize 2.0 (estimated released between Christmas &amp; New Year) is a significant improvement in the minification speed (30% faster should be no exception). As a quick reminder, this is what Autoptimize did until now;</p>\n<ol>\n<li>extract code from HTML &amp; remove original references</li>\n<li>aggregate all code into one string</li>\n<li>check if a minified version of that string exists in cache</li>\n<li>if not in cache;\n<ol>\n<li>minify that string</li>\n<li>store the result in cache</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>inject reference to cached autoptimized code in HTML</li>\n</ol>\n<p>It is the actual minification in step (4) which can slow Autoptimize down (hence <a href=\"http://blog.futtta.be/2014/03/19/how-to-keep-autoptimizes-cache-size-under-control-and-improve-visitor-experience/\">the importance of making sure your cached files are reusable</a>). In Autoptimize 2.0 above logic was changed to improve performance;</p>\n<ol>\n<li>extract code from HTML &amp; remove original references</li>\n<li><strong>aggregate all unminified code</strong> into one string, but only put a <strong>reference to already minified files</strong> (*min.css and *min.js)</li>\n<li>check if a minified version of that string exists in cache</li>\n<li>if not in cache;\n<ol>\n<li>minify that string</li>\n<li><strong>replace references to minified files with </strong>(slightly optimized)<strong> contents</strong></li>\n<li>store the result in cache</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>inject reference to cached autoptimized code in HTML</li>\n</ol>\n<p>As the to-be-minified string is smaller, the JS- &amp; CSS-minifiers have less code to optimize, indeed speeding up the process significantly. Additionally this also <strong>reduces the chances of problems with the re-minification</strong> of already minified code (e.g. p. So nothing but advantages, right?</p>\n<p>Now this was tested rather thoroughly and all known kinks have been ironed out, but If this &#8220;injected minified code late&#8221;-approach does not work in your context, you can <strong>simply disable it by hooking into the API</strong> and setting the <em>autoptimize_filter_js_inject_min_late</em> and/ or <em>autoptimize_filter_css_inject_min_late</em> filters to false (use <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/code-snippets/\">code snippets</a> rather then adding it to your functions.php);</p>\n<pre class=\"brush: php; title: ; notranslate\">add_filter(\'autoptimize_filter_js_inject_min_late\',\'no_late_inject\');\nadd_filter(\'autoptimize_filter_css_inject_min_late\',\'no_late_inject\');\nfunction no_late_inject() {\n	return false;\n}</pre>\n<div class=\'yarpp-related-rss\'>\n<p>Possibly related twitterless twaddle:<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://blog.futtta.be/2014/08/12/next-autoptimize-eliminates-render-blocking-css-in-above-the-fold-content/\" rel=\"bookmark\" title=\"Next Autoptimize eliminates render-blocking CSS in above-the-fold content\">Next Autoptimize eliminates render-blocking CSS in above-the-fold content </a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://blog.futtta.be/2015/08/07/why-autoptimize-doesnt-touch-non-local-cssjs/\" rel=\"bookmark\" title=\"Why Autoptimize doesn&#8217;t touch non-local CSS/JS\">Why Autoptimize doesn&#8217;t touch non-local CSS/JS </a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://blog.futtta.be/2014/12/24/autoptimize-minor-update/\" rel=\"bookmark\" title=\"Autoptimize minor update and beyond\">Autoptimize minor update and beyond </a></li>\n</ul></p>\n</div>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/futtta_autoptimize/~4/uzxbgGOG7_o\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\" alt=\"\"/>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:64:\"http://blog.futtta.be/2015/12/22/making-autoptimize-faster/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\